# Security: Astra Platform Security Policy

These are **hard constraints** from the PRD. Every agent must enforce them. A violation is a **blocking finding**.

## Constraints

### S1: Service-to-service authentication
**All inter-service communication must use mTLS.** No plaintext gRPC or HTTP between services.

Violations include:
- gRPC clients without TLS credentials
- HTTP calls between services without mutual TLS
- Hardcoded service addresses without certificate validation

### S2: User and API authentication
**All external API calls require JWT authentication.** Tokens issued by the `identity` service.

Violations include:
- API gateway endpoints without auth middleware
- Missing JWT validation on any external-facing gRPC/REST endpoint
- Tokens with no expiry or excessively long TTL

### S3: Authorization and RBAC
**All operations must pass OPA policy checks via the `access-control` service.**

Violations include:
- Agent actions bypassing the policy engine
- Missing RBAC checks on tool execution requests
- Admin-only operations accessible to regular agents

### S4: Tool sandbox isolation
**All tool executions must run in sandboxes (WASM/Docker/Firecracker) with least privilege.**

Violations include:
- Tools running in the host process without isolation
- Sandboxes with unrestricted network egress
- Missing resource limits (CPU, memory, disk, time) on tool containers
- Secrets exposed as environment variables in tool sandboxes (must use ephemeral volumes)

### S5: Secrets management
**No secrets in code, logs, or artifacts.** Secrets injected at runtime from Vault.

Violations include:
- Hardcoded API keys, passwords, or tokens in source code
- Secret values logged at any log level
- Secrets persisted in Postgres events or artifact metadata
- `.env` files committed to source control

### S6: Approval gates
**Dangerous actions (infra changes, production deploys, data deletion) require human-in-the-loop approval.**

Violations include:
- Tool executions flagged as dangerous proceeding without approval
- Missing policy-engine intercept on destructive operations

## Enforcement by agent

| Agent | Must verify |
|---|---|
| **architect** | Architecture keeps all comms over mTLS; OPA integrated; sandbox design is sound |
| **db-architect** | No secrets in schema; encryption for sensitive columns; audit trail via events table |
| **tech-lead** | Task specs include security constraints; code review checks for all S1-S6 |
| **go-engineer** | mTLS on all clients; JWT validation; OPA checks; no secrets in logs; sandbox resource limits |
| **devops-engineer** | Helm charts mount TLS certs; Vault integration; network policies isolate namespaces |
| **qa-engineer** | Test plans include security validation; test for auth bypass and sandbox escape |

## Compliance verification

At each approval gate, the approver must include:

```
Security compliance:
- [ ] S1 (mTLS): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
- [ ] S2 (JWT auth): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
- [ ] S3 (RBAC/OPA): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
- [ ] S4 (sandbox isolation): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
- [ ] S5 (secrets management): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
- [ ] S6 (approval gates): [PASS | FAIL | N/A] — [brief note]
```

**Any FAIL is blocking.** Work cannot pass the gate until resolved.
